<td width=485> <P>There are two methods for claiming <A href="http://www.irs.gov/businesses/small/article/0,,id=105708,00.html">business&nbsp;vehicle expenses</A>: actual expenses or the standard mileage rate.</P>
<P>Both begin with complete and accurate mileage records such as a written travel log for each business use of your car or truck. </P>
<P>You can use the records to compute the percentage of business use and apply that against the total car operating expenses for the year.</P>
<P>Or, you can use the records to compute the deduction using the standard mileage rate. The 2007 standard mileage rate for the use of a car (including vans, pickups, or panel trucks) is 48.5 cents per mile for business miles driven.</P>
<P>If you do not have a clear and accurate business mileage record, the IRS may disallow the deduction.</P>
